GitLab Branch Cleanup Automation Strategy1. Objective
To design and implement a centralized, automated branch cleanup process across GitLab repositories that:Identifies stale branches based on last commit activityNotifies responsible contributorsEnforces a configurable grace periodSafely deletes inactive branchesMaintains full auditability
The objective is to improve repository hygiene, reduce clutter, and maintain development efficiency without risking active work.2. Current Challenge
Over time, repositories accumulate:Old feature branchesAbandoned development branchesMerged but undeleted branchesLong-inactive branches
This results in:Repository clutterConfusion for developersIncreased maintenance overheadReduced visibility of active workHigher CI resource usage
GitLab does not provide a built-in automated aging + notification + deletion workflow, therefore a controlled automation solution is required.3. Proposed Solution Overview
Implement a centralized Branch Cleanup Automation Pipeline using:A dedicated automation repositoryGitLab Scheduled CI/CD pipelinesGitLab REST APITwo-phase cleanup model (Notify → Grace → Delete)Controlled exclusion rulesFull audit logging
This solution will be independent of application build pipelines.4. Architecture Overview
4.1 Separate Automation Repository
The cleanup process will be implemented in a dedicated repository, for example:
gitlab-branch-cleanup-automation
This repository will contain:.gitlab-ci.yml (pipeline definition)Cleanup scripts (Python or Shell)Configuration files (projects/groups, exclusions)State tracking filesDocumentation
Important
This cleanup pipeline will be:Completely separate from build/test/deploy pipelinesIndependent of application repositoriesCentrally managedGoverned through controlled permissions
No modifications are required in existing project repositories.5. High-Level System Flow
The automation pipeline will:Run on a schedule (weekly recommended)Use GitLab API to retrieve projectsScan branches in each projectIdentify stale branches based on policyNotify branch ownersStore audit/state recordsAfter grace period, safely delete eligible branchesLog deletions for audit
The pipeline interacts with repositories only via GitLab API — it does not clone or modify source code directly.6. Cleanup Lifecycle (Two-Phase Model)
Phase 1 – Discovery & Notification
Purpose: Identify stale branches and notify owners.
Steps:Retrieve projects (via configured project list or group scan)Retrieve branches for each projectExclude:Default branch (main/master)Protected branchesConfigured exclusion patterns (release/, hotfix/, etc.)Check:Last commit dateOpen Merge RequestsLast commit authorIdentify branches older than threshold (e.g., 90 days)Notify branch ownerRecord candidate branch in state fileGenerate audit report (CSV/JSON artifact)
No branches are deleted in this phase.Phase 2 – Grace Period & Deletion
Purpose: Safely remove branches after waiting period.
Steps:Read candidate list from state fileCheck if grace period has elapsed (e.g., 14 days)Re-validate:Branch still existsStill exceeds inactivity thresholdNo open Merge RequestNot protectedDelete branch via GitLab APILog deletion in audit file
Optional: This stage can require manual approval before execution.7. Proposed Default Policy (Configurable)RuleProposed ValueInactivity threshold90 daysGrace period14 daysSkip open MRsYesSkip protected branchesYesExclude patternsrelease/, hotfix/, production/*Default branch exclusionYesAll values configurable via CI/CD variables.8. Pipeline Design
8.1 Execution ModelImplemented as GitLab CI pipelineTriggered via Scheduled PipelinesRuns weekly for discoveryRuns weekly/daily for deletion phase8.2 Example Pipeline Structure
Stages:discover_notifydelete_after_graceStage 1 – discover_notifyScan configured repositoriesIdentify stale branchesSend notificationsStore candidates in state fileProduce audit artifactStage 2 – delete_after_graceRead state fileCheck grace periodRe-validate eligibilityDelete branchesLog deletions
This stage may:Run automaticallyORRequire manual approval for extra safety9. Repository Structure Example
Example structure of the automation repositgitlab-branch-cleanup-automation/
│
├── .gitlab-ci.yml
├── scripts/
│ ├── discover_notify.py
│ ├── delete_after_grace.py
│
├── config/
│ ├── projects.txt
│ ├── exclude_patterns.txt
│
├── state/
│ ├── pending_deletions.json
│ ├── deleted_log.json
│
└── README.md
10. Authentication & Security Model
A dedicated service account (e.g., branch-cleanup-bot) will be created.
This account will:Be added to required projects/groupsHave minimum necessary role (Developer or Maintainer)Use Personal Access Token or Group Access TokenStore token securely as masked CI/CD variable
This ensures:Controlled permissionsClear audit traceabilityNo dependency on individual user accounts11. Audit & Reporting
Each pipeline run will generate:List of stale branch candidatesNotification logDeleted branch logExecution timestampProject reference
Artifacts retained for compliance and review.
Optional enhancements:Monthly summary reportDashboard metrics12. Safety Controls
To prevent accidental deletion:Mandatory grace periodRe-validation before deletionProtected branch exclusionDefault branch exclusionExclusion pattern supportAudit trailOptional manual deletion approvalDry-run mode available during POC13. Rollout Plan
Phase 1 – Policy AgreementConfirm inactivity thresholdConfirm grace periodConfirm exclusion rulesConfirm notification method
Phase 2 – Proof of ConceptImplement automation repoConfigure limited test repositoriesRun in dry-run modeValidate reports
Phase 3 – Controlled RolloutEnable deletion stageExpand scope graduallyMonitor for one monthMove to full production use14. BenefitsCleaner repositoriesReduced technical debtImproved developer experienceReduced CI loadTransparent governanceFully automated and auditable processZero impact on application pipelinesAssumptions
	
